The expected material yield from **asteroid regolith** varies significantly depending on the **type of asteroid** ‚Äî mainly **S-type**, **C-type**, and **M-type**. For dome construction and industrial processing, the most valuable targets are usually **S-type (stony)** asteroids due to their high content of silicates, metals, and oxides.

Here‚Äôs a breakdown of **typical yields** (by weight %) for the key materials you‚Äôd likely extract per 100 metric tons of raw regolith from an **S-type asteroid**:

---

### üîç **Material Yield Estimates (per 100 tons regolith)**

| Element / Compound | % by Weight | Mass (kg) | Primary Use |
|--------------------|-------------|-----------|-------------|
| **Silica (SiO‚ÇÇ)**  | 20‚Äì25%      | 20,000‚Äì25,000 | Glass, insulation, ceramics |
| **Iron (Fe)**       | 15‚Äì20%      | 15,000‚Äì20,000 | Structural supports, alloys |
| **Nickel (Ni)**     | 1‚Äì2%        | 1,000‚Äì2,000   | Alloying, batteries |
| **Aluminum (as Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ)** | 10‚Äì12% | 10,000‚Äì12,000 | ALON, ceramics |
| **Magnesium (MgO)** | 5‚Äì8%       | 5,000‚Äì8,000   | Alloying, ceramics, glass flux |
| **Calcium (CaO)**   | 3‚Äì5%        | 3,000‚Äì5,000   | Glass flux, construction blocks |
| **Sodium (Na‚ÇÇO)**   | 1‚Äì3%        | 1,000‚Äì3,000   | Glass production, chemical processing |
| **Titanium (TiO‚ÇÇ)** | 2‚Äì5%        | 2,000‚Äì5,000   | Structural alloys, reflective coatings |
| **Chromium / Manganese / Others** | ~0.5‚Äì1% | ~500‚Äì1,000 | Specialized alloying, sensors |
| **Slag & Inert Debris** | 20‚Äì25% | 20,000‚Äì25,000 | Fill, bricks, radiation shielding |

---

### ü™® **Asteroid Type Comparison (Generalized)**

| Asteroid Type | Rich In | Poor In | Notes |
|---------------|---------|---------|-------|
| **S-type**    | Fe, Ni, SiO‚ÇÇ, Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ | Organics, volatiles | Great for structural + dome materials |
| **C-type**    | Volatiles, carbon, water ice | Metals | Good for water + nitrogen sourcing |
| **M-type**    | Fe, Ni, Co | Silicates, volatiles | Ideal for bulk metal processing |

---

### ‚öôÔ∏è Processing Implications

- **ALON Production:** Requires high-purity Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ and AlN, both extractable and synthesizable from S-type or hybrid regolith + volatiles from C-type
- **Dome Glass:** Readily produced from SiO‚ÇÇ, MgO, CaO, Na‚ÇÇO ‚Äî abundant in S-types
- **Titanium:** Extracted as ilmenite (FeTiO‚ÇÉ) or anatase/rutile (TiO‚ÇÇ); reduction can be done with H‚ÇÇ or CO
- **Iron:** Easily magnetically separated and smelted

---

